What is Job Scheduling in Linux?
Job Scheduling in Linux is the process of automatically running commands or scripts at a specific time or interval without manual intervention. It is used to a task for particular time. It is a feature user to execute a command or task at specified time. It is used for the periodic job.

Why we use Job Scheduling
	Automate repetitive tasks
	Reduce manual work
	Ensure tasks run on time
	

Real-World Examples
	Cleaning log files weekly
	Restarting services automatically
	Sending reports daily


CRON JOB
cron is a time-based job scheduler used to run tasks repeatedly (daily, weekly, monthly, etc.).
Cron Daemon
	Service name: crond
	Runs in background
	Executes scheduled jobs
Check cron service
systemctl status crond

Cron Job Syntax 
Cron Format
* * * * * command
Field	Meaning
1st	Minute (0–59)
2nd	Hour (0–23)
3rd	Day of month (1–31)
4th	Month (1–12)
5th	Day of week (0–7)

Example
30 2 * * *   ./backup.sh

Managing Cron Jobs

Edit crontab - edits the current crontab file. If it doesn’t exit, it create one.
crontab -e
List cron jobs - lists the contents of the current users crontab file.
crontab -l
Remove cron jobs - remove jobs/task from crontab file
crontab -r


